DataStructures/Trees/LevelWise.html.title: Level-wise Traversal
DataStructures/Trees/LevelWise.html.body:
Level-wise traversal problems
eg. Top-view, Bottom-view, Thickness of the tree, etc

Can maintain the left-most node and right-most node or related data 
Helper functions or helper data structures (especially collections.deque) for data transfer or retrieval (i.e. depth value or width value) can help

General solution template:
from collections import deque, defaultdict

class Solution:
    def __init__(self):
        self.queue = deque()
        self.level_sum = defaultdict(int)

    def _helperMaxLevelSum(self) -> None:
        while(len(self.queue)):
            node, level = self.queue.popleft()
            if(not node):
                continue

            self.level_sum[level] += node.val

            self.queue.append((node.left, level + 1))
            self.queue.append((node.right, level + 1))

    def maxLevelSum(self, root: TreeNode) -> int:
        self.queue.append((root, 0))
        self._helperMaxLevelSum()

        return max(self.level_sum, key=self.level_sum.get) + 1

Algorithms/BacktrackingAndCompleteSearch.title: Backtracking and Complete Search
Algorithms/BacktrackingAndCompleteSearch.body:
Backtracking and Complete Search
Subsets
Reference: CC Cheat sheet book 
Note the number of recursive calls made
Two choices:

Don't choose the element: Just make a recursive call 
Choose the element
Select step
Go to the next depth
Pop out so that we don't have to instantiate the bucket



class SolutionGenerator:
    def solution_search(self, k : int, domain: list) -> None:
        if (k == self.n):
            self.powerset.append(self.subset[:])
            return
        self.solution_search(k + 1, domain)
        self.subset.append(domain[k])
        self.solution_search(k + 1, domain)
        self.subset.pop()

    def _helper_generator(self, domain: list) -> list:
        self.powerset = []
        self.subset = []
        self.n = len(domain)
        self.solution_search(0, domain)
        return self.powerset

Permutations
Recursive calls for every element in the loop 
No need to add a ‘reject’ scenario 
Accept, make changes and revert after going a level deep 
Filter right after the loop using a helper array used for tracking 
class Permutation:
    def perm_recur(self, k : int, domain: list) -> None:
        if(k == self.n):
            self.permutations.append(self.bucket[:])
            return
        for i in range(0, self.n):
            if(self.accepted[i]):
                continue
            self.accepted[i] = True
            self.bucket.append(domain[i])
            self.perm_recur(k + 1, domain)
            self.accepted[i] = False
            self.bucket.pop()

    def _helper(self, domain: list) -> list:
        self.n = len(domain)
        self.accepted = [False] * self.n
        self.permutations = []
        self.bucket = []
        self.perm_recur(0, domain)
        return self.permutations
